I imagined another way using M4 as the third layer (instead of adding a max threshold on the number of sampled data points in this pr):
1. [raw data layer] Raw time series
2. [transform process layer] (user logic) Transformed time series such as resampling from raw time series
3. [shape-preserving downsampling layer] Further apply M4 sampling to conserve **the shape of the transformed time series** while significantly reducing the number of data points for visualization

For example:
```
1. root.group69.d1701.ZT11529
2. select re_sample(ZT11529,'every'='1m','aggr'='first','interp'='linear') from root.group69.d1701
3. select M4(re_sample(ZT11529,'every'='1m','aggr'='first','interp'='linear'),'timeInterval'='(maxTime-minTime)/w') from root.group69.d1701
```
- `w` is the pixel column width of the visualization screen, such as 1000.
- `maxTime` and `minTime` are the maximal and minimal timestamp of the transformed time series, respectively. You can get them by `select min_time(re_sample(ZT11529,'every'='1m','aggr'='first','interp'='linear')), max_time(re_sample(ZT11529,'every'='30m','aggr'='first','interp'='linear')) into root.tmp(minTime,maxTime) from root.group69.d1701`. Or, adjust the code to allow M4 UDF to calculate `maxTime` and `minTime` at runtime and leave `w` as the only parameter required.

As a result, the output time series of the third layer has no more than 4*w data points (for example 4000) without distorting the shape of the transformed time series.
